        <h3>SSD & HDD (Storage Devices) ⚡💽</h3>

        <p>
            <strong>What they are:</strong>
            SSD (Solid State Drive) is a storage device that uses flash memory chips with no moving parts, making it extremely fast and durable.
            HDD (Hard Disk Drive) is a mechanical storage device that uses spinning disks and a magnetic head to read and write data, offering larger capacities at lower cost.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>What they’re for:</strong>
            SSDs are used for fast system performance, quick boot times, rapid application loading, and smooth overall responsiveness.
            HDDs are used for storing large amounts of data cost-effectively, such as backups, videos, photos, and files that don’t require high-speed access.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>Comparison:</strong>
            SSDs are much faster, quieter, and more durable, but more expensive per gigabyte. HDDs are slower but offer higher storage capacities for a lower price. SSD is ideal for performance; HDD is ideal for mass storage.
        </p>
